              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Loaded beam</h3>
                <svg id="b_beam" class="sa-svg" viewBox="0 0 760 170" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-plots">
                <div class="sa-panel" style="margin:0;">
                  <h3>Shear force V(x) [kN]</h3>
                  <svg id="b_sfd" class="sa-svg" viewBox="0 0 380 220" preserveAspectRatio="none"></svg>
                </div>
                <div class="sa-panel" style="margin:0;">
                  <h3>Bending moment M(x) [kN&middot;m]</h3>
                  <svg id="b_bmd" class="sa-svg" viewBox="0 0 380 220" preserveAspectRatio="none"></svg>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-note" style="margin-top:14px;">Sampled at 320 stations. dV/dx = -w(x); a point load is a step in V, an applied couple is a step in M. The moment peaks where the shear crosses zero.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="sa-prose"><p>To compute the support reactions of a simply-supported or cantilever beam under a point load, a uniformly distributed load and an applied couple, and to construct the shear-force and bending-moment diagrams, locating the maximum bending moment.</p></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="sa-prose">
          <p>For a beam in static equilibrium the sum of vertical forces and the sum of moments about any point both vanish, which gives the reactions of a determinate beam directly. The shear force V(x) at a section equals the algebraic sum of transverse forces to one side of it; the bending moment M(x) is the sum of their moments about the section. Differentially, the slope of the shear diagram is minus the distributed load and the slope of the moment diagram is the shear, so the moment is stationary exactly where the shear is zero. A concentrated point load produces a jump in shear; an applied couple produces a jump in moment.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            Equilibrium:&nbsp; <b>Sum Fy = 0,&nbsp; Sum M = 0</b><br/>
            <b>dV/dx = -w(x),&nbsp; dM/dx = V(x)</b><br/>
            Simply supported, central P:&nbsp; M_max = P&middot;L/4<br/>
            Simply supported, full UDL:&nbsp; M_max = w&middot;L^2/8<br/>
            Cantilever, tip P:&nbsp; M_fixed = -P&middot;L (hogging)
          </div>
          <p>The maximum bending moment governs the bending stress sigma = M&middot;c/I, where c is the distance from the neutral axis to the extreme fibre and I the second moment of area.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="sa-prose"><ol>
          <li>Select simply-supported or cantilever support.</li>
          <li>Set the span L, the point load P and its position a, the UDL intensity w, and any applied couple M0 at position b.</li>
          <li>Read the computed reactions (and fixed-end moment for the cantilever).</li>
          <li>Observe the shear-force diagram and note where it crosses zero.</li>
          <li>Read the maximum bending moment and its location from the moment diagram.</li>
          <li>Sweep the load position a and watch the diagrams and peak moment migrate along the span.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="sa-quiz" data-quiz="sfbm"></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="sa-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>R. C. Hibbeler, Mechanics of Materials, 10th ed., Pearson, Ch. 6.</li>
          <li>S. P. Timoshenko, Strength of Materials, Part I, Van Nostrand.</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs — Strength of Materials, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

      <!-- ================= EXPERIMENT 4: DEFLECTION (MACAULAY) ================= -->
      <section class="sa-experiment" data-exp="defl">
        <h2 class="sa-exp-head">Beam deflection — Macaulay's method</h2>
        <div class="sa-exp-tag">Experiment 4 · Double integration</div>
        <div class="sa-tabs">
          <button class="sa-tab active" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
