        </div>

        <div class="sa-sec active" data-sec="sim">
          <div class="sa-grid">
            <aside>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Support type</h3>
                <div class="sa-seg" id="d_type">
                  <button class="on" data-t="ss">Simply supported</button>
                  <button data-t="cant">Cantilever</button>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Loads</h3>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>Span L (m) <span id="d_LV">8.0</span></label><input id="d_L" type="range" min="2" max="16" step="0.5" value="8"/></div>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>Point load P (kN) <span id="d_PV">40</span></label><input id="d_P" type="range" min="0" max="120" step="2" value="40"/></div>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>Position a of P (m) <span id="d_aV">4.0</span></label><input id="d_a" type="range" min="0" max="16" step="0.25" value="4"/></div>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>UDL w (kN/m) <span id="d_wV">8</span></label><input id="d_w" type="range" min="0" max="40" step="1" value="8"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Flexural rigidity</h3>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>E (GPa) <span id="d_EV">200</span></label><input id="d_E" type="range" min="50" max="400" step="5" value="200"/></div>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>I (10^-6 m^4) <span id="d_IV">120</span></label><input id="d_I" type="range" min="10" max="600" step="10" value="120"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Results</h3>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">EI</span><span class="sa-metric-v" id="d_EI">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Max deflection</span><span class="sa-metric-v green" id="d_dmax">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">at x =</span><span class="sa-metric-v" id="d_dx">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Max slope</span><span class="sa-metric-v amber" id="d_slope">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Deflection / span</span><span class="sa-metric-v purple" id="d_ratio">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Closed-form check</span><span class="sa-metric-v" id="d_cf">—</span></div>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Bending moment M(x) [kN&middot;m]</h3>
                <svg id="d_bmd" class="sa-svg" viewBox="0 0 760 190" preserveAspectRatio="none"></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Elastic curve · deflection (mm), magnified</h3>
                <svg id="d_curve" class="sa-svg" viewBox="0 0 760 230" preserveAspectRatio="none"></svg>
                <div class="sa-formula">EI&middot;y'' = M(x). Macaulay integrates term by term using bracket functions; integrate once for slope theta(x), again for deflection y(x); apply <b>y(0)=y(L)=0</b> (SS) or <b>y(0)=theta(0)=0</b> (cantilever).</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="sa-prose"><p>To compute the slope and deflection of a loaded beam by twice integrating EI&middot;y'' = M(x) with Macaulay's bracket method, applying the support boundary conditions, and to locate and report the maximum deflection against the closed-form standard cases.</p></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="sa-prose">
          <p>The curvature of a slender elastic beam is proportional to the bending moment, giving the governing equation of the elastic curve EI&middot;d2y/dx2 = M(x). Integrating once gives the slope theta(x) = dy/dx and integrating again the deflection y(x), introducing two constants of integration that are fixed by the boundary conditions. Macaulay's method keeps the integration valid across discontinuities by writing each load contribution as a bracket function that switches on only beyond its point of application, so a single expression covers the whole span. For a simply-supported beam the deflection vanishes at both supports; for a cantilever the deflection and the slope both vanish at the fixed end.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            <b>EI&middot;y'' = M(x)</b><br/>
            theta(x) = (1/EI) integral of M dx&nbsp; (+ C1)<br/>
            y(x) = integral of theta dx&nbsp; (+ C2)<br/>
            SS central point load:&nbsp; <b>y_max = P&middot;L^3 / (48&middot;EI)</b><br/>
            SS full UDL:&nbsp; <b>y_max = 5&middot;w&middot;L^4 / (384&middot;EI)</b><br/>
            Cantilever tip load:&nbsp; <b>y_max = P&middot;L^3 / (3&middot;EI)</b>
          </div>
          <p>The slope/deflection here is obtained numerically by trapezoidal double integration of M(x), which reproduces the bracket-function (Macaulay) result and the closed-form cases to plotting accuracy.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="sa-prose"><ol>
          <li>Select simply-supported or cantilever support.</li>
          <li>Set the span L, point load P at position a, and the UDL w.</li>
          <li>Set the Young's modulus E and second moment of area I to define the flexural rigidity EI.</li>
          <li>Read the maximum deflection, its location and the maximum slope.</li>
          <li>Compare the numerical maximum against the closed-form check for the standard case.</li>
          <li>Double I and confirm the deflection halves — it is inversely proportional to EI.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="sa-quiz" data-quiz="defl"></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="sa-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>W. H. Macaulay, "Note on the deflection of beams", Messenger of Mathematics, 1919.</li>
          <li>R. C. Hibbeler, Mechanics of Materials, 10th ed., Pearson, Ch. 12.</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs — Strength of Materials, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

