        </div>

        <div class="sa-sec active" data-sec="sim">
          <div class="sa-grid">
            <aside>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Quantity</h3>
                <div class="sa-seg" id="i_quant">
                  <button class="on" data-t="RA">Reaction R_A</button>
                  <button data-t="RB">Reaction R_B</button>
                  <button data-t="V">Shear at C</button>
                  <button data-t="M">Moment at C</button>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Beam &amp; section</h3>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>Span L (m) <span id="i_LV">10.0</span></label><input id="i_L" type="range" min="4" max="20" step="0.5" value="10"/></div>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>Section C at c (m) <span id="i_cV">4.0</span></label><input id="i_c" type="range" min="0.5" max="19.5" step="0.25" value="4"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Unit load position</h3>
                <div class="sa-ctl"><label>Load at x (m) <span id="i_xV">5.0</span></label><input id="i_x" type="range" min="0" max="20" step="0.1" value="5"/></div>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Readouts</h3>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Ordinate at load</span><span class="sa-metric-v amber" id="i_ord">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Peak ordinate</span><span class="sa-metric-v red" id="i_peak">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">at x =</span><span class="sa-metric-v" id="i_peakx">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Area of IL (+)</span><span class="sa-metric-v green" id="i_area">—</span></div>
                <div class="sa-metric"><span class="sa-metric-l">Live load &middot; ordinate</span><span class="sa-metric-v purple" id="i_eff">—</span></div>
              </div>
            </aside>
            <div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Beam with unit load at x</h3>
                <svg id="i_beam" class="sa-svg" viewBox="0 0 760 150" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="sa-panel">
                <h3>Influence line · ordinate vs unit-load position</h3>
                <svg id="i_il" class="sa-svg" viewBox="0 0 760 240" preserveAspectRatio="none"></svg>
                <div class="sa-formula" id="i_formula">—</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="sa-prose"><p>To construct the influence line for a support reaction, and for the shear and bending moment at a chosen section of a simply-supported beam, by tracking the response as a unit load travels across the span, and to use the ordinates to find the critical position of a moving load.</p></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="sa-prose">
          <p>An influence line is a graph whose ordinate at any position gives the value of a chosen response function — a reaction, a shear or a moment at a fixed section — when a unit load stands at that position. It is fundamental to designing for moving loads such as vehicles on a bridge, because the peak ordinate marks where a single load is most severe and the area under the line scales a distributed load. For a simply-supported span of length L the reaction influence lines are straight lines; the shear and moment influence lines at a section C are piecewise-linear, with a characteristic jump of unit size in the shear line and a peak at C in the moment line.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            Reaction:&nbsp; <b>IL[R_A] = (L - x)/L,&nbsp; IL[R_B] = x/L</b><br/>
            Shear at C (load right of C):&nbsp; <b>V_C = R_A</b>; (load left of C):&nbsp; V_C = R_A - 1<br/>
            Moment at C:&nbsp; <b>IL[M_C] = (L - c)&middot;x/L</b> for x &lt;= c,&nbsp; = c&middot;(L - x)/L for x &gt;= c<br/>
            Peak moment ordinate at C:&nbsp; <b>c&middot;(L - c)/L</b>
          </div>
          <p>For a single moving concentrated load the maximum effect is the load multiplied by the largest ordinate; for a uniform moving load it is the load intensity multiplied by the net positive area under the influence line.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="sa-prose"><ol>
          <li>Choose the response quantity: reaction R_A or R_B, shear at C, or moment at C.</li>
          <li>Set the span L and the position c of the section C.</li>
          <li>Drag the unit-load position x and read the current ordinate from the influence line.</li>
          <li>Note the peak ordinate and the load position that produces it.</li>
          <li>Read the net positive area under the influence line for a distributed moving load.</li>
          <li>Switch quantities and confirm the reaction lines are straight while the moment line peaks at C.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="sa-quiz" data-quiz="infl"></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="sa-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>R. C. Hibbeler, Structural Analysis, 10th ed., Pearson, Ch. 6 (Influence Lines).</li>
          <li>A. Kassimali, Structural Analysis, 6th ed., Cengage, Ch. 8.</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs — Structural Analysis, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

