        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="aim"><div class="sa-prose"><p>To compute the Euler critical buckling load and critical stress of a slender axially-loaded column for four end conditions, to plot the critical stress against slenderness ratio, and to identify where elastic buckling gives way to yielding.</p></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="theory"><div class="sa-prose">
          <p>A perfectly straight elastic column under axial compression remains straight until the load reaches a critical value, above which the straight configuration becomes unstable and the column buckles sideways into a bowed shape. Euler solved the governing equation EI&middot;y'' = -P&middot;y for the buckled equilibrium and found the smallest load for which a non-trivial deflected shape exists. The result depends on the column length, its flexural rigidity and the rotational restraint at the ends, which is captured by an effective-length factor K. The critical stress falls as the square of the slenderness ratio KL/r, so long slender columns buckle elastically at low stress while short stocky columns fail by yielding first.</p>
          <div class="eqs">
            <b>P_cr = pi^2 &middot; E &middot; I / (K&middot;L)^2</b><br/>
            sigma_cr = P_cr / A = <b>pi^2 &middot; E / (K&middot;L/r)^2</b>,&nbsp; r = sqrt(I/A)<br/>
            K = 1.0 pinned-pinned,&nbsp; 0.5 fixed-fixed,&nbsp; 0.699 fixed-pinned,&nbsp; 2.0 fixed-free<br/>
            Valid while sigma_cr &lt;= sigma_y (otherwise the column yields, not Euler buckling)
          </div>
          <p>The transition slenderness, where the Euler stress equals the yield stress, separates the elastic (long-column) regime from the inelastic (short-column) regime; below it Euler's formula over-predicts the strength and an empirical or tangent-modulus curve is used instead.</p>
        </div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="proc"><div class="sa-prose"><ol>
          <li>Select the end condition (pinned-pinned, fixed-fixed, fixed-pinned or fixed-free).</li>
          <li>Set the column length L, the Young's modulus E and the solid round diameter d.</li>
          <li>Read the effective-length factor K, the second moment of area I and the slenderness ratio.</li>
          <li>Read the critical load and critical stress, and see the operating point on the Euler curve.</li>
          <li>Compare the critical stress against the yield cut-off to judge the failure mode.</li>
          <li>Increase the length and watch the critical load fall as 1/L^2 while slenderness rises.</li>
        </ol></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="quiz"><div class="sa-quiz" data-quiz="buck"></div></div>

        <div class="sa-sec" data-sec="ref"><div class="sa-prose"><ul class="refs">
          <li>L. Euler, "Sur la force des colonnes", Memoires de l'Academie de Berlin, 1759.</li>
          <li>S. P. Timoshenko, J. M. Gere, Theory of Elastic Stability, 2nd ed., McGraw-Hill.</li>
          <li>IIT Virtual Labs — Strength of Materials / Structural Stability, vlabs.ac.in.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </section>

